{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_dewitt_ver01/data/sn86090369/00279520750/1908060101/0556.xml":{"full_text":"AI,WAYS READY\nis the Plumber when you need Ills\nservices. At least that is the rule\nwith us\u2014to be \"Johnnle-on-the\nSpot\" for all work when required.\nWe do all kinds of plumbing, new\nwork and repairing, and our meth\nods are praised by all who have\never employed us. We are prompt,\ncareful, thorough In our workman\nship, use none but the best materials\nand, best of all, our charges are\nbased upon strict moderation. Em\nploy us once, and you will always\nconsider us your Plumbers.\nf. S. CR0NR CO.\nMachinists and Plomber\u00b7.\nDealers In Mill, Gin, Plumbing and\nWater Supplies. Metal and Genasco\nRoofing, etc.\nZhe foail\u00e7 Xigbt\npublished daily except\nftUNOAY BY\nThe Enterprise Publishing Co.\nPAID Up\\CAPITAL, $20,000\n\u2014V\u2014\nOFFICEKSAND D1 RECTOR S.\nG. W. McKni\u00e7rhl. President and Treas\nlirer; Ed Cunnmirnam, Vice President; C.\nW. Kent, Secretary. Directors: T. A. Fer\nris, G. W. McKnikht, Ed Cunningham C.\nW. Kent, Dr. C. W.J Simpson.\nr-SUBSCRIPTION RATES\nOne Month M\nSix Months, in advance 2.~5\nOne Year, in advance 5.00\nEntered at the Waxahachie Postoffice as\nMail Matter of the Second Class.\nObituaries, resolutions of respect,cards\nof thanks \u2014all matter not NEWS\u2014will be\ncharged for at t he rate of 5 cents per line.\nPoet ry at double price.\nAny erroneous reflection upon the\ncharacter, standing: or reputation of any\nperson, firm or corporation t hat may ap\npear in the columns of the Daily l,ight\nwill be gladly corrected upon it being\nbrought to the attention of the manage\nment.\nThe Enterprise Publishing Company is\nin no wise responsible for debts that may\nbe contracted by employes, nor will w\u00ab*\nassume payment Of such debts under\nany circumstances. Every employe of\nthis office is paid promptly for work\ndone. This is to protect ourselves and\nthe selling public ENTERPRISE 1M B\u00b7\nLIS H1NG COMPANY. Per G. W. Mc\nKnight. Manager.\nW. A. OWN H Y City Editor,\n\u03b9 Residence Phone, Bell No. 2Si\u00ab.\nCongress has adjourned. There is\nalways something to be thankful for.\nRelieving the distressed within her\nconfines is proving a very ,or\neven iiallas, but to rhe credit of that\ncity be it said that her citizenship is\nresponding nobly to the call for aid.\nSomething must be radically\nwrong down at the A. M. college.\nIn the interest of that institution a\nthorough investigation should be held\nand the blame for trouble properly\nplaced. As things now stand the use\nfulness of the school is entirely de\nstroyed.\nSomething more than suspicion\nshould be required to justify the use\nof the gun as a means of inflicting\nrevenge. Many cases of cold blooded\nmurder are being committed these\ndays and a great number of these\nmurderers are going to be cleared\nor mere suspicions of Justification.\nLooking at you, the Denisou Her\nald says: \"Don't be a stumbling\nblock in the matter of building a\nsolid block of sidewalk where you\nmay own property The building of\na permanent sidewalk through the\nwhole block will prove to be the best\ninvestment you have ever made\nA great many of the older mem\nbers of the Twenty-seventh legisla\nture* will recognize in the published\nphotograph of Hon. R. R. Williams\na gentleman who was at all times as\nsociated with the conservatives and\nfaithful in the performance of his\nduties. Fairness warrants the saying\nof this much in favor of the new as\npirant for governor.\nWe like Senator Senter for several\nreasons, but for Ills own good and\nthe general good ol T< xas democracy\nit is time that ;i gag rule that will\napply t his particular case be origin\nated. This persistent threshing out\nof old straw only aggravates a con\ndition that democrats should be\nearnestly engaged in trying to heal.\nWait until there is a time for fight\ning and then fight.\n\\\\'ithout so much as batting an\nye the Denison Herald hands out\ntills package. If It fits your case 'cuss\nus for reproducing it. The Herald\nsays: The man who sits back and\nI (oj tb< regalt of tin- work of '.tii\np ei foi the advancement of the town,\nnever turning his hand over to help\nhe good work along, may be a good\ncitizen in his own estimation, but,\nas a matter of fact, he ig a barnacle\nand the sooner he is scraped off the\nhitter it will prove to be.\"\nTOO MANY DAIIjY PAI'KIIS.\n\"There is a tide in the affairs of j\nmen which, taken at the flood, leads I\n\u03b9\non to fortune This is an old adage\nand very possibly true, but it is true\ntoo that there Is a time to take back\nwater, for there are times that the\ntide would carry the man who jump\ned, When, a few weeks ago, the then\nproprietor of the News started the\ndaily he had no doubt thought that\nthe tide of affluence was at the\nflood. That may have been true, but\nthe present navigators of this craft\nhave failed to cee any of these signs\nof wealth In the horizon of the\nsheet. In fact, after running for one\nweek they have found the balance\nsheet hanging the wrong way and\nthe wind that leads to fortune has\nevidently changed, for the daily fell\nsome several simoleons to the bad.\nThey made a tour of missionary work\namong the business men yesterday\nand talked to them about the tide of\ntheir affairs, and while the business\nmen were kind and more than kind\nIn their expressions, they were not\nwilling to agree to bind themselves\nto furnish ammunition of war to the\nextent that would cover the defici\nency. Now, the new proprietors are\nnot here for their health; neither\nhave they a barrel from which to\ndraw cash to make a long campaign\nfor success. The meaning of all this\nis the dally is not going to be like\nthe poor\u2014it is not going to be with\nyou always. In fact, with this issue\nit turns up its little pink toes to the j\ndaisies and has gone the way of all\nambitious enterprises that start too\nsoon and get caught in the cold\nfrosts of a wintry world. Is is a great\npleasure to have the plaudits of our\nfriends, but when we tried to get the\nprinters to take their pay in plaudits\nwe found that there was absolutely\nnothing doing.-\u2014Denton Daily News.\nThe Denton Daily News was a\nmorning paper; started In opposition!\nto the Record and Chronicle, an es-I\ntablished afternoon paper. It-recently j\nchanged hands and did not require j\none week for the new proprietors\nwho were good business men, to see\nthe folly of attempting tc continue\ntwo daily papers in a town the size\nof Denton. This story is being con\nst n.tly repeated in Texas towns. On\nsome political or other temporary is\nsue that arises a self-serving promot\ner having all to gain and nothing to\nlose, undertakes, with the backing\nj of a number of local parties having\n\u03b9 personal or special objects to ac\nI compllsh, to launch a daily newspa\nj (tor headway, it perhaps cuts a wide\njswat'i for a time, and then when the\nj issue upon which it was founded\npasses away, the enterprise begins\nI to lag and soon the sheet that start\ned out with a hold flourish of super\niority and the stereotyped declara\njtion that \"we are here to stay,\"\nchanges its tune to one of whining,\nj beseeching and threatening, decry\ning the town, discrediting the pub\nj lie spirit and liberality of its busi\nj ness men, and finally announcing\nj that the promoter \"is npt here for\nhis health,\" and quietly turns up its\ntoes and takes its appropriate place\namong the many similar wrecks\nwhich line the shores of the great\nsea of journalism.\nThe worst sufferers from these\nwreckless ventures in the smaller\ncities and towns are the business men\nwho are called upon to support them\nand often yield to the demands for\npatronage through a mistaken mo\ntive of aiding the community, when\nas a matter of fact, the ultimate out\ncome is detrimental in the extreme to\nthe reputation and progress of the\ncommunity.\u2014Hillsboro Mirror\nFor the sake of peace it would\nI have been much better if precedent\nj had been followed out in the selec\nI lion of district, delegates to the na\nI tional convention, but the fact should\nI not be overlooked that the state con\nvention. in making selections, has\n1 named good men and democrats in\nwhose keeping the honor of Texas\ndemocracy will be safe.\u2014Waxahachie\nLight. The Light opposed Senator\nBailey vigorously during the last\ncampaign, but il now bows gracefully\nto the will of the majority, just as\nall true democrats will do When a\nstrong Bailey man visits Waxahachie\n\u03b9 he will enjoy his visit better if he\nwill call on the editor of the Light\nand drink a glass of Waxabaefaie's\ncool and sparkling and health-giving\nmineral water and he will love his\npartj more. Fort Worth Star.\nTim \u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf <;kt iu s\\\nWithin two months a new legisla\nture will be elected at the democratic\nprimary. This means that it is time\nto quit talking about the thirtieth\nlegislature and to pick the men most\nworthy to compose the lilst list Will\nwe do it? If we do we will do some\nthing we haven't done in lo. these\nmany years.\nit is a favorite practice with Am\nericans to criticize their public ser\nvants between elections and to fail\nto do their duty when they might\nchange the conditions, says the San\nAntonio Light.\nCriticism of the 30th legislature is\nstill reverberating over Texas, yet it j\nis dollars to doughnuts that not 10\nper eent of the critics will exert\nthemselves to secure a higher stand\nard in the next legislature.\nThe people are primarily respon\nsible for all that is done in our gov\nernment, state and national. They\nget just as good service from public\nservants as they deserve. They could\nget the best if they cared enough\nabout it to elect the sort of men from\nwhom the best service is to be ex\npected. Business men, farmers, pro\nfessional men, all classes of citizens\nknow perfectly well that the laws of\ntheir state make or mar the state's\nprosperity; they know that all Indus\ntry is more or less affected favorably\nor adversely by the laws that are\nenacted bl-ennially; they are not\nbackward about expressing their In\ndignation when unwise laws are\npassed, yet they almost invariably do\nnothing to improve the breed of the\nlawmakers.\nRight now is the time when the\ncitizen ought to speak or forever af\nter hold his peace. Candidates for the\nlegislature are out after votes. If the\ncitizen does nothing and the wrong\nman is elected, who is to blame but\nthe citizen? Remember, failure to\nvote on the part of any good citizen\nis always equivalent to casting half\na vote for the unfit candidate.\nHONKSTY IN THE WORM\u00bb.\nThe press heralds and the world\ngazes w.'h wonder and scorn at the\ndishonest bank official, and yet lit\ntle attention is paid to the thousands\nof honest officials. A bank has its\nsafety deposit vaults built of con\ncrete and armor plate and guarded\nwith time locks to ward off the bur\nglar. and yet in any of them an un\nderpaid bank clerk can work havoc,\nand how few out of the many take\nadvantage of the opportunities offer\ned?\nTo be sure, there are audits and\nchecks against dishonesty on the\npart of the clerks and officials, but\nthe exception proves the rule, and\nafter all it is upon the integrity and\nhonesty of humanity that Safety of\nhundreds of millions of portable and\ntransportable property depends.\nIt is in this sterling honesty of the\nvast majority of men that hope lies,\nand even the pessimists who see\nnothing but evil in the world cannot\nblind their eyes to the facts \u2014Beau\nmont Enterprise.\nPRFSISVTKRIAN ORPHAN HO.MK\nThere Is \u03b7 Nerd of Funds to Sus\ntain Institution.\nItasca. Texas. June 1 .\u2014Publication\nis requested for the following, which\nis addressed to \"all friends of the\norphans in Texas:\"\nA word as to the orphans in the\nTexas Presbyterian home and school\nat Files. The health of the children\ncontinues good, l^ey having escaped\nthe measles, mumps and smallpox,\nwhich have been all around us.\nThere are forty-seven children\nnow in the home, with three more\nexpected by June 1. and a number\nof applications pending.\nWe have just sent out our first or\nphan, oil account of reaching the age\nof 18, at which time they go from\nthe home for themselves. Happily,\nin this case, the young lady goes out\ninto a home of her own, having been\nmarried on the 20th of this month to\na worthy young man of the commun\nity.\nThe school has gone on regularly,\nand will continue to do so for sever\nal weeks, and the children seem to\nbe making good progress.\nThe boys, under the supervision of\nthe superintendent of tjie farm, are\ncultivating about sixty or seventy\nacres in corn, cotton and garden,\nand are harvesting this week a good\ncrop of oats and hay.\nThe new building is progressing\nnicely, being now ready for the roof,\nand is to be completed by August 1.\nWhen completed we will be able to\nhouse from ninety to 100 children,\nbesides having two good school\nrooms and a chapel.\nOn the whole, the work and con\ndition of the home was never in bet\nter shape and with brighter pros\npects. Only one thing looks dark to\nthose in charge\u2014and that is the re\nceipts for May have for some reason\nfallen short, and we have scarcely\nenough money to meet our monthly\nbills. This fact causes great anxiety\non the part of the management, as\nthis is the beginning of the sum\nmer. when on account of absence\nfrom home on the part of many, the\nreceipts at all orphanages are small\ner than at other times,\nSend all offerings to the treasurer\nor directly to me.\nJAMES I) McLEAN, President.\nsix \\TToKNKVs disiiarrki\u00bb.\nVe. used of (ironing in Sale of Land\nFor Veterans.\nWashington. June 1.\u2014Six promin\nent Washington attorneys have been\ndisbarred from practice in the de\npartment of the interior after today\nIt is alleged that they sought out old\nsoldiers or their widows to whom\nland grants had not been issued, and\ninformed them that such land could\nbe had on application. When the\nwarrants were issued the lawyers ad\nvised the holders that the land could\nbe sold at a nominal figure. In most\ncases the veterans would agree, the\nland becoming the property of the\nlawyers, who sold it at a large prof\nIt.\nThe lawyers (Msbarrei are Thos.\nR. Harney and Eugene E. 3tevens,\nforming the firm of Mllo B. Stevens\nCo.: Harvey Spaulding, Edwin W\nSpauldlng and James H. Spaulding.\nforming the firm of 11. Spaulding\nSons, and Edgar P. Gaddis.\nCAR \u039f\u039f\u039a\u039d.\nJust arrived. D. H Thompson. !jl\nPHOSPKUJTY BOOM.\nMen Were Given Employment jtl si.\nLouis.\nSt. Louis, June 1.\u2014Thousands of\nmpn thrown out of employment dur\ning the business and financial de\npression are back in their old places\ntoday, as the result of a concerted\nplan of all manufacturing and com\nmercial concerns in the city to make\nthis employment day.\" The project\nhad its origin with the National\nprosperity Association, the \"let us\nalone\" body, and has been generally\ntaken up by the business interests of\nthe c'ty.\nAmong the big concerns which\ncelorrated \"prosperity day\" were the\nFerguson-McKinney Dry Goods Co..\nwhich put hack 1,000 employes tem\nporarily dropped from the pay rolls\nduring the financial depression, and\nth Ely Walker Dry Goods com\npany. which today started every ma\nchine in its factories and gave em\nployment to 2,000 men and women.\nMany other concerns employed\nsmaller numbers of workmen and\nthe movement has been taken up by\nthe railroads and other corporations.\nThere is a feeling of confidence that\n\"employment day\" marks the full\nreturn of prosperity to St. Louis, and\nit is likely that the plan followed\nhere will be taken up in many other\ncities throughout the country.\nBIG CLASS AT ANNAPOLIS.\nMore Than Two Hundred Will Re\nceive Diploma\u00bb This Year.\nAnnapolis, Md., June 1.\u2014The lar\ngest, class that ever left the Annapo\nlis Naval Academy at one time will\nbe graduated this week, the com\nmencement week exercises for the\n200 midshipmen beginning today\nwith the official reception to the\nboard of visitors. During the next\nfour days there will be the usual\nround of drills and practical exer\ncises. Friday will be commencement\nday, and it is expected that Secretary\nMetcalf will deliver an address and\npresent the diplomas to the gradu\nates. On Saturday the first, second\nand third classes will embark on the\nseveral ships of the cruising squad\nron fftr the annual winter cruise. The\nclass to be graduated, will be the\nlargest that ever left the institution\nat any one time before. It contains\n200 members. The class of 1907 was\nlarger by eight members than this\nveer's class, but was graduated in\nthree separate divisions, one section\nof eighty-six receiving diplomas in\nSeptember. 1906. a second section\nof fifty being graduated in Febru\nary, 1907. while the last section of\nseventy-two was graduated at the\nregular time in June.\nTHE CLOSING EXERCISKS.\nOral (Examinations Will Be Conduct\ned Tuesday Morning.\nTomorrow morning from 9 o'clock\nuntil 12, oral examinations will be\nconducted in all rooms of the High\nschool building. The quizzes\nwill be on the work of the year and\nwill prove interesting. There will also\nbe other interesting and entertain\ning exercises in the primary grades.\nWednesday morning from 9 to 12,\nthere may be seen In each room an\nexhibition of the v.-ork actually doue\nthis term. This exhibition will con\nsist of maps, drawings, sketches, out\nlines. themes, mountings, written\nrecitations on various subjects, etc.\nWednesday evening at 8:15 in the\nHigh school auditorium will be held\nthe regular graduating exercises.\nRev. J. B. Boen will address the class\nand award diplomas. Music will be\nfurnished by the Wise Orchestra.\nTWO MUX DROWN.\nFishermen Kail Into Kden's Tank\nNear Corslcana.\nCorsicana, Texas, June 1.\u2014Paul\nBreckner, a baker of this place, and j\na Mr. Curry of \u03a4\u03b9 ;ue were drowned I\nSunday morning hile fishing in j\nEden's tank, about two''miles north j\nof town.\nBreckner was sitting on a root of j\na tree over the water and started for\nthe shore, when he slipped and fell\ninto the water and was drowned be-\nfore assistance could reach him.\nCurry, who was lying on a plank in\nthe water, seeing Breckner fall, be\ncame excited and lost his balance,\nfalling into the water and was also\ndrowned. Breckner was 2.i years old\n\u03b9 and leaves a wife and child.\n\u00c0h.\nFor Cleanliness and Comfort\nUSE, AN\nElectric Flatiron\n\nWe install them on 30 days trial \u0396\n\n\nWaxahachie Electric 4 Gas\nCOMPANY I\nStari the New Month Right\nBuy a sack of\n\"TOWN TALK\" FLOUR\nand you will be in a good humor with the\ncuok as long as it lasts, and then you'll\nbuy more.\nFor sale by the leading grocers.\nModern Milling MTg Co.\nDR. J. D. HODGE,\nVETERINARY SURGEON\nWaxahachie, Texas\nSe\u00efcntwn Years Experience\nTreats all domestic animals,\nspecialist In Eye and Dentaf\nWork, removes successfully\nPoll Evil, Fistulas, Tumors\nand Cancer Warts.\nExamination and consultation\nFree. Bring your Stock\naround and have them exam\nined.\nKEINNINGHAM'S STABLE.\nBoth Phones. Waxahachie.\nr\nFOR\nRESULTS\nTRY A WANT AD\n\u2014IN\u2014\nTHE DAILY LIGHT\nTHEY PAY\nBEST.\nPublicity Ttirouglf the Printer\ns\nHERE has been a phenomenal growth in all lines\nof business in the past few years. The small\nhouse of a few years ago is the strong concern\nof today. The old house of a few years ago is\ntoday only a memory. Young blood and younger\nmethods have displaced the old business as the elec\ntric car has displaced the mule car, except in Waxa\nhachie, and as the lightning express has displaced the\npost chase of our grandfathers.\nThe man who buys does not upend his\ntime hunting over the various stores of|\nthe town. He, consults his newspapers\nor his magazines.\nm\nHESE remarkable strides in business have not\nbeen the result of chance or \"good luck\", but of\nfar-sighted business judment, assisted by mod\nern methods. No one thing has contributed so\nmuch to the wonderful success of the modern busi\nness house over the old time one, as ADVERTISING.\nPublicity in all forms is today recognized as the one\nessential to success of the man who has something to\nsell.\nr\nEnterprise Publishing Co\n\n\u03bf\n\u03bf\n\u03b2\n\u03bf\n\u03bf\n\u03b8\n\u03bf\n\u03bf\n\u03bf\n\u03bf\n\u03b8\n\u03bf\n\n\n\u039f\u03b9\n8\n\n\u03bf\n\u03bf\ns\n\u03bf\n\u03b2\n\u03bf\n\u03bf\n\n\n\u03bf\n\u03bf\n\n\n\u03b8\n\u03bf","height":"25852","width":"18060"}}
